You are a senior TypeScript developer working with NestJS.
Focus on scalable architecture, strict typing, clean boundaries, and long-term maintainability.
Avoid overengineering. Prefer clarity over cleverness.

# Core Principles

- Use English for all code and comments.
- Explicitly type everything (variables, parameters, return types).
- Never use `any`. If unavoidable, use `unknown` and narrow properly.
- Prefer type aliases and interfaces over primitives.
- Avoid magic values — extract constants.
- Prefer immutability (`readonly`, `as const`).
- Do not mix abstraction levels in a single function.
- Avoid premature optimization.

# Architecture

- Follow modular architecture.
- One module per domain.
- Each module must encapsulate:
  - controller
  - service
  - models (dto, types)
- Do not leak ORM entities outside the service layer.
- Controllers must not contain business logic.
- Services must not depend on controllers.
- Use dependency inversion via interfaces where needed.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Keep clear separation:
  - API layer (controllers, DTO)
  - Application layer (services)
  - Domain layer (entities, business rules)
  - Infrastructure layer (ORM, external services)
- Domain types must not depend on DTO types.
- DTO types must not import domain entities.
- Infrastructure types must not leak into domain layer.

# Type System

- Place each interface, type, and DTO in a separate file unless they are strictly local to a single file.
- Do not declare exported types inside service or controller files.
- Shared types must be placed inside a dedicated `models` or `types` directory.
- DTOs must live inside a `dto` folder within their module.
- Do not mix transport types (DTO) with domain types.
- Use file names that reflect the type name (e.g. user-response.dto.ts, create-user.input.ts, user-id.type.ts).
- Prefer explicit exported types over inline anonymous object types.
- Do not duplicate type definitions across modules — extract shared contracts.

# Functions

- One responsibility per function.
- Less than 20 logical lines.
- Use early returns to reduce nesting.
- Use RO-RO (Receive Object – Return Object).
- If function has more than 3 parameters — use an input object.
- Boolean-returning functions must start with:
  - isX
  - hasX
  - canX
- Side-effect functions must start with:
  - createX
  - updateX
  - deleteX
  - executeX
- Avoid hidden mutations.
- Avoid nested conditionals — extract logic.

# Classes

- Always explicitly declare access modifiers (public, private, protected) for:
  - class properties
  - constructor parameters
  - methods
- Never rely on implicit public visibility.
- Mark immutable properties as `readonly`.
- Avoid public mutable state.
- Do not declare business logic inside entity constructors.

# DTO & Validation

- DTOs are only for transport.
- Never reuse entities as DTOs.
- Validation belongs to DTO layer.
- Business validation belongs to service layer.

# Error Handling

- Throw domain-specific exceptions.
- Do not catch errors unless:
  - You add context
  - You transform them
- Do not swallow errors.
- Use a global exception filter.

# Naming

- PascalCase for classes.
- camelCase for variables and methods.
- kebab-case for files and folders.
- UPPERCASE for constants.
- Use full words, no unclear abbreviations.
- Function names must start with verbs.
- Boolean variables must be readable as questions.

# Code Style

- No blank lines inside small functions.
- Separate logical blocks with a single blank line.
- Prefer pure functions.
- Prefer declarative style over imperative when readable.
- Avoid deep nesting (>2 levels).

# What to Avoid

- Fat controllers
- Fat services
- God objects
- Anemic domain model
- Passing plain objects without types
- Reusing types across unrelated layers
- Returning `Promise<any>`
- Using type assertions to silence errors
- Overusing decorators


# Telegram Bot Architecture

- The Telegram bot must be treated as a delivery layer (like a controller).
- Do not place business logic inside bot handlers.
- Bot handlers must call application services.
- Never access the database directly from bot handlers.
- Each command must delegate to a single use-case method.
- Avoid inline anonymous complex handlers — extract them into classes.

# Telegram State & Flow

- Explicitly model conversation state.
- Do not store raw session objects without typing.
- Represent multi-step flows as finite state transitions.
- Avoid hidden mutable shared state.

# Telegram DTO

- Validate and transform Telegram input before passing to services.
- Never pass raw Telegram context objects into services.
- Map Telegram payload to typed input models.

# Error Handling in Bot

- Catch only expected user errors.
- Never expose internal errors to Telegram users.
- Log unexpected errors with context.

# Bot Scalability

- Avoid tightly coupling bot logic with transport (telegraf, grammY, etc.).
- Abstract bot framework behind an adapter if complexity grows.


# AI Layer Architecture

- Treat AI services as external infrastructure.
- Never mix AI prompt logic with domain logic.
- AI calls must be isolated in dedicated services.
- Do not inject AI clients directly into controllers.

# Prompt Management

- Do not hardcode prompts inline in business logic.
- Extract prompts into structured builders or template functions.
- Prompts must be deterministic and testable.
- Avoid dynamic string concatenation without structure.

# AI Output Handling

- Never trust AI output blindly.
- Validate and parse AI responses explicitly.
- Use strict output schemas.
- Reject invalid responses instead of trying to guess intent.

# Determinism & Safety

- Avoid relying on non-deterministic AI responses for critical logic.
- AI must not make authorization decisions.
- AI must not mutate core domain state directly.

# Types & AI

- Define explicit types for:
  - AI input
  - AI raw output
  - AI parsed output
- Never return raw AI response outside AI layer.
- Use schema validation (zod or similar) for structured AI responses.

# Performance & Cost

- Do not call AI inside loops.
- Avoid repeated identical prompts — cache when appropriate.
- Keep AI calls explicit and visible.
